We know it's hard to decide if a piece of technology is going to be any use for you, and without trying it you just can't tell, so we're setting up Digital Dementia Resource Centres (DDRCs) where you can try things and have a chat to someone impartial. #dementiahacks @alzscot

Our first Digital Dementia Resource centre is in Kilmarnock.  You can speak to the staff there about things like the Ring Doorbell which might help with cold callers, or motion sensor lighting, and even better, you can try it out for yourself. #dementiahacks @alzscot

As  well as being able to try pieces of technology and talk to staff about them at our Digital Dementia Resource Centres, there are links beside each of them to dementia circle, where you'll find reviews about them from families living with dementia. #dementiahacks @alzscot

If you're interested in finding out more about our Digital Dementia Resource Centres, please drop us a message or have a look on https://t.co/bVzMuf1B5V for details about the devices that can be tried.
See you back here next week for another Tech Tuesday!

"Digital dementia" is a term coined by the German neuroscientist Manfred Spitzer in his 2012 book Digitale Demenz. He describes how overuse of technology is causing the kind of short-term memory dysfunction and breakdown of cognitive abilities.

Who is at risk of digital dementia? Millions of smartphone users, for a start. The average person checks their smartphone every 12 minutes, according to a 2018 Ofcom report. One in five of us spend more than 40 hours a week online. That's more than five hours a day.

1. What is Digital Dementia?

Digital Dementia is a modern day health epidemic resulting in a sensory mismatch in the brain from over utilization of technology and excessive slouched sitting posture.

2. Signs and symptoms of Digital Dementia include:

Slouched posture, Developmental delays, Short-term memory loss, Social seclusion, Lack of movement, Anxiety, Depression, Anger, Balance disorders, and Uncoordinated movement patterns.

3. How does Digital Dementia develop?

When individuals spend an excessive amount of time on their devices with poor posture a sensory dissociation occurs where the back of the brain is overactive and the front of the brain is under active.

4. Some ways to prevent and overcome Digital Dementia

Minimise screen time.
Maintain a proper posture.
